'''Saint Martin''' ({{lang-fr|Saint-Martin}}), officially the '''Collectivity of Saint Martin''' (French: ''CollectivitÃ© de Saint-Martin'') is an [[overseas collectivity]] of [[France]] located in the [[Caribbean]]. It came into being on 15 July 2007,<ref>The French law was passed in February 2007, but the new status came in force once the local assemblies elected, with second leg of the vote on 15th July 2007. See J. P. Thiellay, ''Droit des outre-mers'', Paris:Dalloz, 2007.</ref> encompassing the northern parts of [[Saint Martin]] island and neighbouring [[islet]]s, the largest of which is [[Ãle Tintamarre]]. The southern part of the island, [[Sint Maarten]], is one of the four constituent countries that form the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]].
==Politics and government== Saint Martin was for many years a French [[commune in France|commune]] forming part of [[Guadeloupe]], which is an [[DÃ©partement d'outre-mer|overseas ''rÃ©gion'' and ''dÃ©partement'']] of France and is therefore in the [[European Union]]. In 2003 the population of the French part of the island voted in favour of [[secession]] from Guadeloupe in order to form a separate [[CollectivitÃ© d'outre-mer|overseas collectivity]] (COM) of France.<ref>{{cite news |first = |last = |author = Staff reporter |coauthors = |title = French Caribbean voters reject change |url = http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2003/12/09/voters.htm |work = |publisher = Caribbean Net News |pages = |page = |date = 9 December 2003 |accessdate = 9 February 2007 |quote = However voters on the two tiny French dependencies of Saint-Barthelemy and Saint-Martin, which have been administratively attached to Guadeloupe, approved the referendum and are set to acquire the new status of "overseas collectivity". }}</ref> On 9 February 2007, the [[French Parliament]] passed a bill granting COM status to both the French part of Saint Martin and (separately) the neighbouring [[Saint BarthÃ©lemy]].<ref>{{cite news |first = |last = |author = Staff reporter |coauthors = |title = Saint-Barth To Become An Overseas Collectivity |url = http://www.st-barths.com/jsb/pdf_files/weekly107.pdf |format = PDF |work = |publisher = St. Barth Weekly |pages = |page = 2 |date = 9 February 2007 |accessdate = 9 February 2007 |quote = }}</ref> The new status took effect once the local assembly was elected on 15 February 2007.<ref>[http://www.newmedia-fr.info/ixm_ixpnews.php?file=article&story_id=21579 Les Ã©lections du futur conseil territorial font dÃ©bat - Politique - Nouvelles sur Newmedia.fr - New Media : Infos Guadeloupe, Martinique, Guyane, Saint-Martin, Saint-BarthelÃ©my, CaraÃ¯bes - Infos Newmedia.fr<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Saint Martin remains part of the [[European Union]].<ref>The [[Treaty of Lisbon]] states that Saint-Martin is a part of the EU. See: {{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:C:2008:115:0047:0199:EN:PDF|title=Treaty of Lisbon, Article 349 and 355|accessdate=18 March 2010}}.</ref>
The new governance structure befitting an overseas collectivity took effect on 15 July 2007 with the first session of the Territorial Council ({{lang-fr|Conseil territorial}}) and the election of [[Louis-Constant Fleming]] as president of the Territorial Council. On 25 July 2008 Fleming resigned after being sanctioned by the [[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'Ãtat]] for one year over problems with his 2007 election campaign.<ref>{{cite news |first = |last = |author = Staff reporter |coauthors = |title = Louis-Constant Fleming dÃ©missionnÃ© par le conseil dâEtat |url = http://www.fxgpariscaraibe.com/article-21561959.html |work = |publisher = fxgpariscaraibe |pages = |page = |date = 28 July 2008 |accessdate = 17 August 2008 |language = french }}</ref> On 7 August, [[Frantz Gumbs]] was elected as President of the Territorial Council.<ref>{{cite news |first = |last = |author = Staff reporter |coauthors = |title = Frantz Gumbs elected new president of CollectivitÃ© |url = http://news.caribseek.com/Sint_Maarten/The_Daily_Herald/article_68029.shtml |work = |publisher = The Daily Herald |pages = |page = |date = 8 August 2008 |accessdate = 17 August 2008 |language = |quote = Frantz Gumbs, formerly president of Union Pour le ProgrÃ¨s (UPP) party, swept into power as new president of the CollectivitÃ© at an extraordinary meeting of the Territorial Council on Thursday after winning the 23-councillor vote with a clear majority over Marthe OgoundÃ©lÃ©-Tessi. }}</ref> However, his election was declared invalid on 10 April 2009 and [[Daniel Gibbs]] appointed as Acting President of the Territorial Council on 14 April 2009.<ref>http://www.thedailyherald.com/news/daily/l278/shamel278.html</ref> However, Gumbs was reelected on 5 May 2009.<ref>http://rulers.org/2009-05.html</ref>
Before 2007, Saint Martin was coded as GP ([[Guadeloupe]]) in [[ISO 3166-1]]. In October 2007, it received the [[ISO 3166-1|ISO 3166-1 code]] MF (alpha-2 code), MAF (alpha-3 code), and 663 (numeric code).<ref>ISO 3166-1 Newsletter. [http://www.iso.org/iso/newsletter_vi-1.pdf Assignment of code elements for Saint BarthÃ©lemy and Saint Martin and update of France and other French Territories]</ref> {{Saint Martin Territorial Council election, 2007}}
=== Coat of arms === The '''coat of arms of the French overseas collectivity [[Saint-Martin]]''' features a ship, a palm and a sun, and reads "CollectivitÃ© de Saint Martin".<ref>[http://groups.yahoo.com/group/flags/files/GP/gp-saint_martin.gif]</ref> The comune that existed until February 22, 2007, used similar arms but with the legend "Ville de Saint Martin".<ref>[http://www.st-martin.org/upload/file/pdf/reflet.pdf]</ref> <ref>[http://www.internationalspecialreports.com/archives/00/stmaarten/6.html]</ref>
==Demographics== The French part of the island has a land area of 53.20&nbsp;square kilometres (20.5 sq mi). A local English-based [[Virgin Islands Creole|dialect]] is spoken in informal situations on both the French and Dutch sides of the island.<ref>Holm (1989) ''Pidgins and Creoles,'' vol. 2</ref> At the January 2007 French census, the population in the French part of the island was 35,925 (up from only 8,072 inhabitants at the 1982 census), which means a [[population density]] of {{convert|675|PD/km2}} in 2007. {| align="center" rules="all" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" style="border: 1px solid #999; border-right: 2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background: #f3fff3" |+ style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 0.5em"| Historical population ! 1885!! 1961!! 1967!! 1974!! 1982!! 1990!! 1999 !! 2006 !! 2007 |- | align=center| 3,400 || align=center| 4,502 || align=center| 5,061|| align=center| 6,191 || align=center| 8,072 || align=center| 28,518 || align=center| 29,078 || align=center| 35,263 || align=center| 35,925 |- | colspan=9 align=center| <small>Official figures from French censuses. |}
==Economy== [[Image:Marigot flags St Martin.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Flags flying in Marigot harbour, Saint-Martin.]]
The official currency of Saint Martin is the [[euro]], though the [[United States dollar|US dollar]] is also widely accepted. Tourism is the main economic activity.
[[INSEE]] estimated that the total [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] of Saint Martin amounted to 421 million euros in 1999 (US$449 million at 1999 exchanges rates; US$599 million at Oct. 2007 exchange rates).<ref name=GDP>{{Fr icon}} {{cite web| url=http://www.insee.fr/fr/insee_regions/guyane/publi/PIB_IDN.pdf| title=Estimation du PIB de Saint-BarthÃ©lemy et de Saint-Martin| author=[[INSEE]], CEROM| format=PDF|accessdate=13 November 2007}}</ref> In that same year the GDP per capita of Saint Martin was 14,500 euros (US$15,500 at 1999 exchanges rates; US$20,600 at Oct. 2007 exchange rates), which was 39% lower than the average GDP per capita of [[metropolitan France]] in 1999.<ref name=GDP /> In comparison, the GDP per capita on the Dutch side of the island, Sint Maarten, was 14,430 euros in 2004.<ref>Total 2004 GDP of Sint Maarten ([http://www.cbs.an/SNA/SNA93%20P12B.asp]) divided by the number of inhabitants in 2004 ([http://www.cbs.an/population/population_b2.asp]), then converted from [[Netherlands Antillean gulden]] to euro by using the 2004 exchange rate.</ref>
